</div></section></section><section id="sec16"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">Risk of Cerebrovascular Events</h3>
<p>The incidence of events was highest in patients who underwent radiotherapy alone compared with any other treatment group (<em>P</em> &lt; .001). Specifically, by 5 years after diagnosis, actuarial incidence of cerebrovascular events was 19% in patients who underwent radiotherapy alone compared with 14% in patients who underwent surgery plus radiotherapy and 14% in patients who underwent surgery alone; the corresponding actuarial incidences by 10 years after diagnosis were 34%, 25%, and 26%, respectively (<a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>, <a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Fig 1</a>). However, there was no significant difference between incidence of cerebrovascular events in the combined group of patients who underwent any radiotherapy (with or without surgery; 29%) and patients who underwent surgery alone (26%; Appendix Fig A1, online only).</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T3"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 3.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>Actuarial Incidence of Cerebrovascular Events by Treatment Group</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="hsides" rules="groups">
<thead>
<tr>
<th colspan="1" rowspan="2" align="center" valign="bottom">Treatment</th>
<th colspan="1" rowspan="2" align="center" valign="bottom">No. of Events per 1,000 Person-Years</th>
